# MemoryAI Coding-Guard — Cursor Rules

Apply when the task produces or modifies code. Skip pure docs/Q&A/chat.

## Per-mode behavior
- **Ask**: clarify; surface tradeoffs; no edits unless asked.
- **Edit**: surgical only; no adjacent cleanup.
- **Agent**: state plan, execute, verify via build/tests, paste exit code.

## 1. Think before coding
State assumptions explicitly. Surface multiple interpretations. Push back when a simpler approach exists. Unclear → STOP, name the confusion, ASK.

## 2. Simplicity first
Minimum code. No speculative abstractions, flexibility, or impossible-error handling. Senior-engineer test: would they call this overcomplicated?

## 3. Surgical changes
Every changed line traces to the request. Match existing style. Mention dead code, don't delete it. Remove only orphans YOUR change created.

## 4. Goal-driven execution
Define verifiable success: failing test → passing, build green, exit 0. Loop until verified.

## Anti-sloppy gates (HARD RULES)
- No "done" claim without build/test exit code pasted as evidence.
- Out-of-scope refactor requires explicit approval.
- Never silently skip/xfail tests, never `--no-verify`, never comment out asserts.
- Edits touching >5 files: post plan first, await ack.
- Quote the failing assertion before claiming a fix.
- Verify imports against `package.json`/lockfile before writing.
- Reference files via `#file:path` — never guess paths.
- 2 fails same way → STOP, diagnose root cause, no mechanical retry.
- `rm -rf`, `git push --force`, `git reset --hard`, `DROP TABLE` → require explicit confirm.

## Verification
Use the project's actual commands and paste the exit code:
- Node: `npm test && npm run lint && npm run build`
- Python: `pytest -x && ruff check . && mypy .`
- Go: `go test ./... && go vet ./... && go build ./...`
- Rust: `cargo test && cargo clippy -- -D warnings`
